(1) I am going to give more context here, NOT because I feel I need to justify myself to an empathy lacking troll, but because I think these things are important to talk about. None of my pregnancies
(2) were unintentional. The first time, I was married and 30 years old. I got pregnant first month trying. I was so very excited to become a mother. My husband and I couldn’t wait. Then, at 7 weeks I
(3) started bleeding. I remember being in shock because for some reason I didn’t think miscarriage would happen to me (naive, I know). I was tearing up in the doctors office and she said “you know,
(4) this loss is so early it doesn’t really even count as a pregnancy” when I asked if we could please investigate the root cause of the miscarriage. That statement literally cut like a knife as it
(5)uttered to me in the middle of me grieving a real to me loss. But, I really really wanted to be a mom so I tried again. And we lost another pregnancy. And another. Finally I was referred to a
(6) fertility specialist who was able to help us sustain a pregnancy, which resulted in the birth of my daughter. But I had to endure lots of hormonal treatments and lived in fear for 9 months that I
(7) would lose her too. And she was delivered c section which has left me with very painful adhesions and bladder issues. Those symptoms came later though. Anyway, my husband and I wanted to give our
(8) daughter a sibling, so we did the fertility treatments again. The 5th pregnancy resulted in a full term stillbirth and was the absolute most traumatic thing I’ve ever been through. We were left

(9) with making the decision of giving up or trying again and because we love being parents, we decided to try again. My 6th and final pregnancy resulted in the premature birth of my son and a uterine
(10) rupture. This is the cliffs notes version of it all but yeah. We kept trying and kept putting ourselves through it because we wanted to be parents and wanted a family. But it WAS traumatic,
(11) physically & mentally. Both things can be true. Again, if anyone doesn’t understand, just be grateful you don’t.
